The '''Tunisia national football team''', represents [[Tunisia]] in men's international [[association football]] competitions, and is controlled by the [[Tunisian Football Federation]] (TFF). The team competes under the [[Confederation of African Football]] (CAF) on the continental level, and is affiliated with [[FIFA]] for global competitions. Additionally, the team is a member of the [[UNAF|Union of North African Football]] (UNAF) and the [[Union of Arab Football Associations]] (UAFA). The team is colloquially known as ''Eagles of [[Carthage]]'' by fans and the media, with the [[bald eagle]] serving as its symbol.<ref>{{Cite web |title="Carthage Eagles" home glory |url=https://www.cafonline.com/total-africa-cup-of-nations/news/carthage-eagles-home-glory |access-date=19 April 2022 |website=CAF |language=en}}</ref> Their home kit is primarily white and their away kit is red, which is a reference to the [[Flag of Tunisia|national flag]] of the country. The team has qualified for the [[FIFA World Cup]] seven times and the [[Africa Cup of Nations]] 22 times, and has appeared in four editions of [[Football at the Summer Olympics|Summer Olympics]] and participated once in the [[FIFA Confederations Cup|FIFA Confederation Cup]]. Since 2001, Tunisia's home stadium is the [[Hammadi Agrebi Stadium]] in [[Radès]], Tunis.

Tunisia's first match after independence was against [[Libya national football team|Libya]], which they won 4–2. The team qualified for the FIFA World Cup for the first time in [[1978 FIFA World Cup|1978]] as the only representative of the continent, and became the first African and Arab team to win a World Cup match by beating [[Mexico national football team|Mexico]] [[1978 FIFA World Cup Group 2#Tunisia vs Mexico|3–1]] in the first game. Tunisia holds the most consecutive appearances in the Africa Cup of Nations, with 17, qualifying for every tournament between [[1994 African Cup of Nations|1994]] and [[2025 Africa Cup of Nations|2025]]. By winning the [[2004 African Cup of Nations]], they qualified for the [[2005 FIFA Confederations Cup]] and was eliminated in the group stage. The team qualified twice for the [[African Nations Championship]], winning the title in their first appearance in [[2011 African Nations Championship|2011]], while also competing in the [[FIFA Arab Cup]] three times, winning the title in the inaugural edition in [[1963 Arab Cup|1963]] and finishing second in [[2021 FIFA Arab Cup|2021]]. [[Radhi Jaïdi]], with 105 international matches, holds the record for the number of matches played for Tunisia while [[Issam Jemâa]], with [[List of international goals scored by Issam Jemâa|36 goals]], is their all-time highest scorer. Their highest-ever [[FIFA Men's World Ranking]] was 14th in April and May 2018, while their lowest rank was 65th in July 2010.<ref>{{Cite web |date=12 April 2018 |title=Classement mondial FIFA: L'équipe de Tunisie est classée 14ème mondiale réalisant le meilleur classement de son histoire. |trans-title=FIFA World Ranking: Tunisia team ranked 14th in the world, achieving the best ranking in its history |url=https://www.ftf.org.tn/fr/classement-mondial-fifa-lequipe-de-tunisie-est-classee-14eme-mondiale-realisant-le-meilleur-classement-de-son-histoire/ |access-date=19 September 2024 |website=[[Tunisian Football Federation]] |language=fr-FR}}</ref> 

On 13 October 2025, Tunisia became the first team in history to qualify for the World Cup without conceding a goal, during the [[2026 FIFA World Cup qualification – CAF Group H|2026 World Cup qualifying]] campaign.{{fact|date=June 2026}}

==History==
{{Main|History of the Tunisia national football team}}

=== 1928–1956: French protectorate of Tunisia and beginning ===
[[File:Sélection_tunisienne.jpg|right|thumb|The Tunisian football team in 1939.]]
Before independence, an unofficial team was formed in 1928, comprising the best Tunisian players from the [[Tunisian Ligue Professionnelle 1|Tunisian League]]. The team's first match was on 11 March 1928, against the [[France national football B team]]; Tunisia lost 8–2.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=texte |first1=Parti socialiste SFIO (France) Auteur du |last2=texte |first2=Parti socialiste (France) Fédération (Paris) Auteur du |date=12 March 1928 |title=Le Populaire : journal-revue hebdomadaire de propagande socialiste et internationaliste ["puis" socialiste-internationaliste] |url=https://gallica.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/bpt6k819267p |access-date=3 August 2020 |website=Gallica |language=EN}}</ref> Their next friendlies, against the same team on 23 March 1930 and 26 March 1933, also resulted in heavy defeats: 0–5 and 1–6 respectively.

Tunisia had to wait until 1932 for their first match win: a 1–0 victory over [[French Algeria]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=2 May 2022 |title=Tunisia v Algeria, 13 November 1932 |url=https://www.11v11.com/matches/tunisia-v-algeria-13-november-1932-224236/ |website=11 v 11 |language=EN}}</ref> Most of the matches that Tunisia played in the 30s and 40s were against French teams, whether it was French Algeria, the [[International Military Sports Council|French military team]] or the France B team, in addition to a match against the [[France national football team|France national team]] in 1941. Most of these matches were played at the [[Stade El Menzah#History|Stade Vélodrome]] in [[Tunis]].

=== 1956–1962: Post independence, First international participation ===
Tunisia gained [[Tunisian independence|independence]] from France on 20 March 1956. The [[Tunisian Football Federation]] was founded on 29 March 1957 and the Tunisian team played a match with Austrian club [[FC Admira Wacker Mödling]] on 30 December of the same year, winning 4–1. Tunisia became affiliated with [[FIFA]] and the [[Confederation of African Football]] in 1960. The independent Tunisia played their first match against [[Algeria national football team|Algeria]] on 1 June 1957, in the midst of the [[Algerian War]], in which Tunisia lost 2–1. They played their first official match at the [[1957 Arab Games]] where they won against [[Libya national football team|Libya]] 4–3 after scoring the first Tunisian goal in an official competition by {{ill|Brahim Ben Miled|fr|Brahim Ben Miled|lt=Farzit}}. They won against [[Iraq national football team|Iraq]] 4–2 and [[Lebanon national football team|Lebanon]] 4–2 before losing in the final against [[Syria national football team|Syria]] 3–1. In 1960, Yugoslavian [[Milan Kristić]] became the first foreign manager. The national team qualified for the [[1960 Summer Olympics]], their first international event after beating [[Malta national football team|Malta]], [[Morocco national football team|Morocco]] and [[Sudan national football team|Sudan]]. In the Olympic Games, the team suffered three defeats: against [[Poland national football team|Poland]] 6–1, [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]] 2–1, and [[Denmark national football team|Denmark]] 3–1. [[Frane Matošić]] was appointed as the second Yugoslav coach of Tunisia after Kristić led Tunisia to qualify for the Olympics.

=== 1962–1978: Golden generation, First World Cup participation ===
[[File:Tunisia football team 1978.jpg|thumb|Tunisia at the [[1978 FIFA World Cup qualification]] against Egypt.]]

In 1962, Tunisia entered the [[1962 African Cup of Nations qualification|African Cup of Nations qualifiers]] for the first time. The team qualified for the tournament after beating [[Morocco national football team|Morocco]] and [[Nigeria national football team|Nigeria]], and went on to finish third after beating [[Uganda national football team|Uganda]] in the third-place match. The team won the [[1963 Arab Cup]], after winning against Syria, [[Jordan national football team|Jordan]], Lebanon, and [[Kuwait national football team|Kuwait]]. Tunisia also qualified for the [[1963 Africa Cup of Nations]], and [[Confederation of African Football|CAF]] decided that Tunisia would host the [[1965 Africa Cup of Nations|1965 AFCON]], making the final after beating [[Ethiopia national football team|Ethiopia]] 4–0 in the opening match in [[Stade Chedly Zouiten]],<ref>{{Cite web|title=Tunisia - Ethiopia 4:0|url=https://www.flashscore.com/match/bqReoLuQ/#match-summary|access-date=3 August 2020|website=www.flashscore.com|language=en}}</ref> losing 3–2 to [[Ghana national football team|Ghana]] in extra-time of the final.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Ghana - Tunisia 3:2|url=https://www.flashscore.com/match/biNeyyII/#match-summary|access-date=3 August 2020|website=www.flashscore.com|language=en}}</ref> Despite this early success, Tunisia did not enter the Cup of Nations again until 1976, and did not qualify until 1978. In 1973, the team entered the [[1973 Palestine Cup of Nations|Palestine Cup of Nations]] and won in dominant fashion, winning all six of their matches overcoming Syria, [[Egypt national football team|Egypt]], [[Palestine national football team|Palestine]], [[Yemen national football team|Yemen]] and Iraq, scoring 19 goals. In February 1975, after a short stint with Hungarian manager [[André Nagy]], [[Abdelmajid Chetali]] was hired. Tunisia qualified for their [[FIFA World Cup]] debut in [[1978 FIFA World Cup|1978]]. Tunisia defeated Mexico 3–1,<ref>{{Cite web |title=Tunisia - Mexico 3:1 |url=https://www.flashscore.com/match/SED70PSJ/#match-summary |access-date=23 April 2022 |website=www.flashscore.com |language=en}}</ref> but were defeated by [[Poland national football team|Poland]] 1–0,<ref>{{Cite web |title=Poland - Tunisia 1:0 |url=https://www.flashscore.com/match/nafve3js/#match-summary |access-date=23 April 2022 |website=www.flashscore.com |language=en}}</ref> and drew scoreless against defending champion [[West Germany national football team|West Germany]].

=== 1978–1994: Decline and Missing six editions of the AFCON ===
After their inaugural World Cup, Tunisia experienced a decline. Between 1980 and 1992, the team managed to qualify for only two tournaments: the [[1982 African Cup of Nations]], and the [[Football at the 1988 Summer Olympics|1988 Summer Olympics]]. In both, they were knocked out in the first round. They, however, reached the last round of the [[1986 FIFA World Cup|1986 World Cup qualifiers]] by beating Nigeria before being defeated by [[Algeria national football team|Algeria]]. Former [[Cameroon national football team|Cameroon]] manager [[Jean Vincent]] was hired but the team was unable to qualify for the [[1988 Africa Cup of Nations|1988 African Cup]] in Morocco after a defeat against Algeria.

The team experienced poor results in the [[1987 All-Africa Games|African Games]] with defeats against Cameroon, [[Madagascar national football team|Madagascar]] and [[Kenya national football team|Kenya]]. [[Taoufik Ben Othman]], assistant manager in 1978,<ref>{{Cite web |title=Olympedia – Taoufik Ben Othman |url=https://www.olympedia.org/athletes/27449 |access-date=17 August 2022 |website=www.olympedia.org}}</ref> improved Tunisia's results, as they qualified for the Olympic Games after surpassing [[Morocco national football team|Morocco]] and [[Egypt national football team|Egypt]] in the qualifiers. However, he was removed days before the start of the competition after poor results in the [[1988 Arab Cup]] and failure to win in their matches against [[Saudi Arabia national football team|Saudi Arabia]],<ref>{{Cite web |title=Saudi Arabia v Tunisia, 11 July 1988 |url=https://www.11v11.com/matches/saudi-arabia-v-tunisia-11-july-1988-241224/ |access-date=17 August 2022 |website=11v11.com}}</ref> Lebanon,<ref>{{Cite web |title=Tunisia v Lebanon, 17 July 1988 |url=https://www.11v11.com/matches/tunisia-v-lebanon-17-july-1988-241244/ |access-date=17 August 2022 |website=11v11.com}}</ref> Egypt<ref>{{Cite web |title=Egypt v Tunisia, 13 July 1988 |url=https://www.11v11.com/matches/egypt-v-tunisia-13-july-1988-241230/ |access-date=17 August 2022 |website=11v11.com}}</ref> and Iraq,<ref>{{Cite web |title=Iraq v Tunisia, 09 July 1988 |url=https://www.11v11.com/matches/iraq-v-tunisia-09-july-1988-241219/ |access-date=17 August 2022 |website=11v11.com}}</ref> as well as friendlies against [[Malta national football team|Malta]], [[Finland national football team|Finland]] and East Germany. Polish manager [[Antoni Piechniczek]] was temporarily appointed and supervised the team in the first round of 1990 World Cup qualifiers and also in the finals of the Olympic Games; in the latter, Tunisia tied [[China national football team|China]] 0–0<ref>{{Cite web |title=Tunisia - China 0:0 |url=https://www.flashscore.com/match/WAIVmxtp/#match-summary |access-date=17 August 2022 |website=www.flashscore.com |language=en}}</ref> and [[Sweden men's national football team|Sweden]] 2–2<ref>{{Cite web |title=Sweden - Tunisia 2:2 |url=https://www.flashscore.com/match/UHEnfv3G/#match-summary |access-date=17 August 2022 |website=www.flashscore.com |language=en}}</ref> and lost to [[West Germany national football team|West Germany]] 4–1.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Tunisia - Germany 1:4 |url=https://www.flashscore.com/match/CQyagbIM/#match-summary |access-date=17 August 2022 |website=www.flashscore.com |language=en}}</ref> [[Mokhtar Tlili]] was appointed manager, however, he still missed the [[1990 Africa Cup of Nations|African Cup]] in 1990 after a defeat to Senegal. Piechniczek returned but still failed to qualify for the 1990 World Cup.{{Context inline|date=October 2024|reason=Who?}} Despite missing the [[1992 Africa Cup of Nations|1992 African Cup]], the federation renewed confidence in him because of the respectable performance he had given in the qualifiers; an early exit from the World Cup qualifiers for [[1994 FIFA World Cup|1994]] contributed to his dismissal after a draw with Morocco.{{Context inline|date=October 2024|reason=This doesn't sufficiently explain information regarding the appointment of the coaches. This reads like "He was appointed and then removed when the team failed to qualify."
Tell me WHEN he was removed with precise dates. If it isn't that important, why does this need to be in the article at all?}} [[Youssef Zouaoui]] replaced him; Tunisia hosted the 1994 African Cup of Nations replacing original hosts [[Zaire]], but finished at the bottom of the group, after a 2–0 loss to Mali<ref>{{Cite web |title=Tunisia - Mali 0:2 |url=https://www.flashscore.com/match/A9kJPykM/#match-summary |access-date=17 August 2022 |website=www.flashscore.com |language=en}}</ref> and a draw with Zaire.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Tunisia - D.R. Congo 1:1 |url=https://www.flashscore.com/match/bakbKFCq/#match-summary |access-date=17 August 2022 |website=www.flashscore.com |language=en}}</ref>

=== 1994–2002: Beginning of Resurgence, 1996 AFCON runners-up ===
[[Henryk Kasperczak]] became the new manager after Tunisia hosted the 1994 African Cup of Nations. Tunisia qualified for the [[1996 African Cup of Nations|1996 AFCON]] and finished second in their group, putting them through to the quarter-finals. Tunisia went on to beat [[Gabon national football team|Gabon]] in the quarter-finals and [[Zambia national football team|Zambia]] in the semi-finals,<ref>{{Cite web |title=Gabon - Tunisia 1:2 |url=https://www.flashscore.com/match/GAhdbjCo/#match-summary |access-date=17 August 2022 |website=www.flashscore.com |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Zambia - Tunisia 2:4 |url=https://www.flashscore.com/match/2Rf8eld4/#match-summary |access-date=17 August 2022 |website=www.flashscore.com |language=en}}</ref> to reach their first major final in 31 years, but lost to host country [[South Africa national football team|South Africa]] 2–0.<ref>{{Cite web |title=South Africa - Tunisia 2:0 |url=https://www.flashscore.com/match/2BCPgSQG/#match-summary |access-date=17 August 2022 |website=www.flashscore.com |language=en}}</ref> Tunisia reached the quarter-finals of the [[1998 African Cup of Nations]] in the lead of the group with a win over [[DR Congo national football team|DR Congo]],<ref>{{Cite web |title=Tunisia - D.R. Congo 2:1 |url=https://www.flashscore.com/match/EDb5faHR/#match-summary |access-date=17 August 2022 |website=www.flashscore.com |language=en}}</ref> [[Togo national football team|Togo]] and a defeat from [[Ghana national football team|Ghana]],<ref>{{Cite web |title=Tunisia - Togo 3:1 |url=https://www.flashscore.com/match/0lHmlcfe/#match-summary |access-date=17 August 2022 |website=www.flashscore.com |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Ghana - Tunisia 2:0 |url=https://www.flashscore.com/match/pvf1eu2L/#match-summary |access-date=17 August 2022 |website=www.flashscore.com |language=en}}</ref> where they were eliminated in a penalty shootout by host country [[Burkina Faso national football team|Burkina Faso]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Tunisia - Burkina Faso 1:2 |url=https://www.flashscore.com/match/SxSlNH0K/#match-summary |access-date=17 August 2022 |website=www.flashscore.com |language=en}}</ref>  The team also qualified for [[1998 FIFA World Cup|that year's World Cup]] after a 20-year absence: they again failed to advance from the group stages, losing 2–0 to [[England national football team|England]] and 1–0 to [[Colombia national football team|Colombia]],<ref>{{Cite web |title=England - Tunisia 2:0 |url=https://www.flashscore.com/match/lxMpmznS/#match-summary |access-date=17 August 2022 |website=www.flashscore.com |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Colombia - Tunisia 1:0 |url=https://www.flashscore.com/match/KKCGsE9k/#match-summary |access-date=17 August 2022 |website=www.flashscore.com |language=en}}</ref> and drawing 1–1 with [[Romania national football team|Romania]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Romania - Tunisia 1:1 |url=https://www.flashscore.com/match/tz1Puhv2/#match-summary |access-date=17 August 2022 |website=www.flashscore.com |language=en}}</ref> Kasperczak was sacked and replaced with [[Francesco Scoglio]], who guided the team to the [[2000 African Cup of Nations]], where they finished in fourth place after losing to [[Cameroon national football team|Cameroon]] in the semi-finals.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Cameroon - Tunisia 3:0 |url=https://www.flashscore.com/match/tx2sJTGq/#match-summary |access-date=17 August 2022 |website=www.flashscore.com |language=en}}</ref> The following year, Scoglio departed to rejoin [[Genoa CFC]], sparking a period of severe instability. [[Eckhard Krautzun]] initially took over and guided the team to a second [[2002 FIFA World Cup|World Cup]] appearance, but then resigned, citing interference from the [[Tunisian Football Federation|Tunisian FA]] with his coaching. [[Henri Michel]] replaced him, but was sacked when Tunisia crashed out of the [[2002 African Cup of Nations]] without scoring a single goal after scoreless draws with [[Senegal national football team|Senegal]] and Zambia and a defeat from Egypt. Finally, [[Ammar Souayah]] took over in time for the 2002 World Cup; the team drew in friendlies with Norway and South Korea and were defeated by Denmark and Slovenia. In the finals, Tunisia exited the tournament in the group stage, drawing 1–1 with [[Belgium national football team|Belgium]], losing 2–0 to [[Russia national football team|Russia]] and co-hosts [[Japan national football team|Japan]],<ref>{{Cite web |title=Tunisia - Belgium 1:1 |url=https://www.flashscore.com/match/4Eu4yLEe/#match-summary |access-date=17 August 2022 |website=www.flashscore.com |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Russia - Tunisia 2:0 |url=https://www.flashscore.com/match/W0sdwspq/#match-summary |access-date=17 August 2022 |website=www.flashscore.com |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Tunisia - Japan 0:2 |url=https://www.flashscore.com/match/IHq8zuU1/#match-summary |access-date=17 August 2022 |website=www.flashscore.com |language=en}}</ref> prompting a search for a new manager.<ref>{{Cite web |title=La Tunisie se prépare à la CAN 2004 |url=https://lematin.ma/journal/2003/La-Tunisie--se-prepare-a-la-CAN-2004/28669.html |access-date=17 August 2022 |website=Le Matin |date=4 May 2003 |language=fr}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Coupe d'afrique des nations de Football en Tunisie CAN 2004 |url=https://coupedafrique.winoo.com/can2004/stades/Stade.cfm?stade=3 |access-date=17 August 2022 |website=coupedafrique.winoo.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=26 January 2004 |title=CAN 2004: c'est parti |url=https://www.nouvelobs.com/sport/20040125.OBS3064/can-2004-c-est-parti.html |access-date=17 August 2022 |website=L'Obs |language=fr}}</ref>

=== 2002–2008: Roger Lemerre era, 2004 AFCON champions ===
[[File:Tunisia - Netherlands (Stade de Radès) 3.jpg|thumb|Tunisia against [[Netherlands national football team|Netherlands]] in a friendly game at the [[Hammadi Agrebi Stadium|7 November Stadium]] in 2009.]]
In September 2002, the [[Tunisian Football Federation]] announced that it was finalizing a contract with former France manager [[Roger Lemerre]]. Tunisia hosted the [[2004 African Cup of Nations]], winning the group.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Tunisia - Guinea 1:1|url=https://www.flashscore.com/match/UmNCefKB/#standings;table|access-date=1 December 2021|website=www.flashscore.com|language=en}}</ref> They defeated Senegal in the quarter-finals,<ref>{{Cite web|title=Tunisia - Senegal 1:0|url=https://www.flashscore.com/match/fqrhJU2T/#match-summary|access-date=1 December 2021|website=www.flashscore.com|language=en}}</ref> and Nigeria in the semi-finals. Tunisia built a 1–0 lead after four minutes with [[Mehdi Nafti]]'s concentration pushed by [[Francileudo Santos]], before Morocco levelled. Tunisia restored their lead,<ref>{{Cite web|title=Tunisia - Morocco 2:1|url=https://www.flashscore.com/match/67TRZkmA/#match-summary|access-date=1 December 2021|website=www.flashscore.com|language=en}}</ref> giving them their first [[Africa Cup of Nations|African Cup of Nations]] title. They also won the CAF's African National Team of the Year award. Lemerre became the first manager to win two different continental tournaments, having previously won [[UEFA Euro 2000|Euro 2000]] with France. As a result, Tunisia qualified for the [[2005 FIFA Confederations Cup]] in Germany, playing the hosts, [[Argentina national football team|Argentina]] and [[Australia men's national soccer team|Australia]]. The only points they would win was a victory over Australia.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Argentina - Tunisia 2:1|url=https://www.flashscore.com/match/As9oDQ2a/#match-summary|access-date=1 December 2021|website=www.flashscore.com|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=Tunisia - Germany 0:3|url=https://www.flashscore.com/match/MPz2B4XB/#match-summary|access-date=1 December 2021|website=www.flashscore.com|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=Australia - Tunisia 0:2|url=https://www.flashscore.com/match/ruPA9r2O/#match-summary|access-date=1 December 2021|website=www.flashscore.com|language=en}}</ref> Before their 2006 World Cup appearance, Lemerre took the Tunisians to a training camp in Switzerland, where they played international friendlies against Swiss clubs. Tunisia would only record one draw in Germany, against Saudi Arabia, losing against [[Spain national football team|Spain]] and [[Ukraine national football team|Ukraine]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=Ukraine - Tunisia 1:0|url=https://www.flashscore.com/match/rmDeruhJ/#match-summary|access-date=1 December 2021|website=www.flashscore.com|language=en}}</ref> [[Hatem Trabelsi]] announced his retirement from international football after eight years,<ref>{{Cite web|date=21 February 2018|title=Hatem Trabelsi |work=National Football Teams|url=http://www.national-football-teams.com:80/player/6730/Hatem_Trabelsi.html|access-date=1 December 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180221022708/http://www.national-football-teams.com:80/player/6730/Hatem_Trabelsi.html|archive-date=21 February 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=20 May 2018 |title=FIFA Tournaments - Players & Coaches - Hatem TRABELSI |url=http://www.fifa.com:80/fifa-tournaments/players-coaches/people=170770/index.html |access-date=1 December 2021 |website= |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180520095227/http://www.fifa.com:80/fifa-tournaments/players-coaches/people=170770/index.html |archive-date=20 May 2018 |url-status=dead}}</ref> and Lemerre led Tunisia to the 2008 African Cup of Nations. Tunisia won their 2008 AFCON group after a draw in the opening match against Senegal 2–2, a 3–1 victory over South Africa, and a goalless draw against Angola. They then lost against [[Cameroon national football team|Cameroon]] 3–2 in extra time.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Tunisia - Cameroon 2:3 |url=https://www.flashscore.com/match/l2XD4DFF/#match-summary |access-date=1 December 2021 |website=www.flashscore.com |language=en}}</ref>

=== 2008–2014: Disappointments and missing the World Cup ===
[[File:Ivory Coast vs Tunisia 2013 AFCON.jpg|thumb|Tunisia against Ivory Coast at the [[2013 Africa Cup of Nations]] in South Africa.]]

Portuguese [[Humberto Coelho]] was appointed as the new manager on 3 June 2008. Coelho would fail to qualify for the 2010 World Cup. [[Faouzi Benzarti]] was appointed as the new manager, and was also sacked after Tunisia were eliminated from the group stage in the [[2010 Africa Cup of Nations]]. In June 2010, [[Bertrand Marchand]] was appointed manager for a two-year contract. After a series of horrendous results, Tunisia fell to 65th in the [[FIFA World Rankings]], the worst in its history. [[Sami Trabelsi]] was appointed, and the team qualified for the [[2012 Africa Cup of Nations]], where they were eliminated in the quarter-finals after a defeat by [[Ghana national football team|Ghana]].

In the [[2013 Africa Cup of Nations]], Tunisia snatched a late winner against [[Algeria national football team|Algeria]], before a defeat by [[Ivory Coast national football team|Ivory Coast]], 3–0. The last match ended with a 1–1 draw against [[Togo national football team|Togo]]. In February 2013, [[Nabil Maâloul]] replaced Sami Trabelsi; in their first two [[2014 FIFA World Cup qualification (CAF)|2014 World Cup qualification]] matches, Tunisia beat Sierra Leone 2–1 and clinched a 2–2 draw in [[Freetown]]. On 16 June, during the fifth round of the group stage, Tunisia tied 1–1 against Equatorial Guinea. A 2–0 loss to Cape Verde on 7 September all but eliminated Tunisia; however, Tunisia advanced after FIFA disqualified Cape Verde for cheating. They would then be knocked out by Cameroon.

=== 2014–2022: Renaissance and two World Cup participations ===
[[File:Bel-Tun (23).jpg|thumb|Tunisia against Belgium at the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]] in Russia.]]
[[File:Contrôle de balle tunisien.jpg|thumb|Tunisia against Mali at the [[2021 Africa Cup of Nations]] in Cameroon. The match stopped at the 85th minute.]]
[[File:Tunisia 0 - 0 Denmark (FIFA World CUP 2022).jpg|thumb|Tunisia against Denmark at the [[2022 FIFA World Cup]] in Qatar.]]
Belgian manager [[Georges Leekens]] was appointed in early 2014; early results included a 1–1 draw against [[Colombia national football team|Colombia]] and a 1–0 win over [[South Korea national football team|South Korea]],<ref>{{Cite web|title=Colombia - Tunisia 1:1|url=https://www.flashscore.com/match/8Ct7uOS7/#match-summary|access-date=3 August 2020|website=www.flashscore.com|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=South Korea - Tunisia 0:1|url=https://www.flashscore.com/match/INedKt71/#match-summary|access-date=3 August 2020|website=www.flashscore.com|language=en}}</ref> both in friendly matches. Under Leekens, the team climbed from 49th to 22nd in the FIFA rankings. Tunisia qualified for the [[2015 African Cup of Nations]], and topped their group for the first time since 2008, winning against [[Zambia national football team|Zambia]] and drawing with [[Cape Verde national football team|Cape Verde]] and [[DR Congo national football team|DR Congo]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=Zambia - Tunisia 1:2|url=https://www.flashscore.com/match/CxLpBtin/#match-summary|access-date=3 August 2020|website=www.flashscore.com|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=Tunisia - Cape Verde 1:1|url=https://www.flashscore.com/match/beEY3PqJ/#match-summary|access-date=3 August 2020|website=www.flashscore.com|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=D.R. Congo - Tunisia 1:1|url=https://www.flashscore.com/match/pjJh9KLb/#match-summary|access-date=3 August 2020|website=www.flashscore.com|language=en}}</ref> They were eliminated in the quarter-finals after a defeat to host [[Equatorial Guinea national football team|Equatorial Guinea]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=Tunisia - Equatorial Guinea 1:2|url=https://www.flashscore.com/match/0l26giuo/#match-summary|access-date=3 August 2020|website=www.flashscore.com|language=en}}</ref> In July 2015, [[Henryk Kasperczak]] returned as manager after 17 years. He managed to qualify the team for the [[2017 Africa Cup of Nations|2017 African Cup]], and reached the quarter-finals of the competition after beating Algeria and [[Zimbabwe national football team|Zimbabwe]],<ref>{{Cite web|title=Algeria - Tunisia 1:2|url=https://www.flashscore.com/match/M5B8KeYT/#match-summary|access-date=3 August 2020|website=www.flashscore.com|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=Zimbabwe - Tunisia 2:4|url=https://www.flashscore.com/match/vNuNwJYi/#match-summary|access-date=3 August 2020|website=www.flashscore.com|language=en}}</ref> before losing against [[Burkina Faso national football team|Burkina Faso]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=Burkina Faso - Tunisia 2:0|url=https://www.flashscore.com/match/r1cuHWMo/#match-summary|access-date=3 August 2020|website=www.flashscore.com|language=en}}</ref>

On 27 April 2017, [[Nabil Maâloul]] returned as manager despite the disapproval of the Tunisian supporters following the failure at the 2014 World Cup qualifiers, but this time he qualified Tunisia for the [[2018 FIFA World Cup|2018 World Cup]] in Russia. Tunisia's qualification for the World Cup and its results in friendlies against [[Iran national football team|Iran]] and [[Costa Rica national football team|Costa Rica]],<ref>{{Cite web|title=Tunisia - Iran 1:0|url=https://www.flashscore.com/match/ClJnoE32/#match-summary|access-date=3 August 2020|website=www.flashscore.com|language=en}}</ref> led to its rise to 14th place in the [[FIFA World Rankings]], their best ever. Before the World Cup, Tunisia drew with [[Turkey national football team|Turkey]] and [[Portugal national football team|Portugal]],<ref>{{Cite web|title=Portugal - Tunisia 2:2|url=https://www.flashscore.com/match/SGgwGtU8/#match-summary|access-date=3 August 2020|website=www.flashscore.com|language=en}}</ref> in addition to a narrow defeat against Spain 1–0.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Spain - Tunisia 1:0|url=https://www.flashscore.com/match/dMdR34c8/#match-summary|access-date=3 August 2020|website=www.flashscore.com|language=en}}</ref> Despite this, in the World Cup, Tunisia were once again eliminated from the group stage. In the first match,<ref>{{Cite web|title=Tunisia - England 1:2|url=https://www.flashscore.com/match/COm14u4S/#match-summary|access-date=3 August 2020|website=www.flashscore.com|language=en}}</ref> [[England national football team|England]] won 2–1.<ref>{{cite web|date=18 June 2018|title=England kick off campaign with hard-fought victory|url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/russia2018/matches/match/300331554/#match-summary|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180618185206/https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/russia2018/matches/match/300331554/#match-summary|archive-date=18 June 2018|website=FIFA.com|publisher=Fédération Internationale de Football Association}}</ref> [[Belgium national football team|Belgium]] defeated the North Africans 5–2,<ref>{{Cite web|title=Belgium - Tunisia 5:2|url=https://www.flashscore.com/match/I5QTaaCq/#match-summary|access-date=3 August 2020|website=www.flashscore.com|language=en}}</ref> and in Tunisia's last game against [[Panama national football team|Panama]],<ref>{{Cite web|title=Panama - Tunisia 1:2|url=https://www.flashscore.com/match/4MSuccd2/#match-summary|access-date=3 August 2020|website=www.flashscore.com|language=en}}</ref> the Arab nation won 2–1.<ref>{{cite web|last=Chowdhury|first=Saj|date=28 June 2018|title=Wahbi Khazri scores as Tunisia end with 2-1 win over Panama|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/44439319|work=BBC Sport}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|date=28 June 2018|title=Second-half surge sees Tunisia bow out in style|url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/russia2018/matches/match/300331520/#match-summary|website=FIFA.com|publisher=Fédération Internationale de Football Association}}</ref> Tunisia qualified for the [[2019 Africa Cup of Nations]] with new manager [[Alain Giresse]]; the new manager would only record three ties, against [[Angola national football team|Angola]], [[Mali national football team|Mali]], and [[Mauritania national football team|Mauritania]] to qualify for the round 16. They eventually would win against [[Ghana national football team|Ghana]], and [[Madagascar national football team|Madagascar]] 3–0 in the quarter-finals, to qualify for the semi-finals for the first time in 15 years, losing to [[Senegal national football team|Senegal]] 1–0 in extra time. In September 2021, the national team began its [[2022 FIFA World Cup qualification]] campaign with three consecutive victories against Equatorial Guinea, Zambia,<ref>{{Cite web |title=Zambia vs. Tunisia - 7 September 2021 - Soccerway |url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2021/09/07/africa/wc-qualifying-africa/zambia/tunisia/3500828/ |access-date=19 December 2021 |website=int.soccerway.com}}</ref>  and Mauritania; they would then draw Mauritania 0–0 and lose against Equatorial Guinea 1–0, to advance for the [[2022 FIFA World Cup qualification – CAF third round|third round]] on the top of [[2022 FIFA World Cup qualification – CAF second round#Group B|the group]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Equatorial Guinea vs. Tunisia - 13 November 2021 - Soccerway |url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2021/11/13/africa/wc-qualifying-africa/equatorial-guinea/tunisia/3500834/ |access-date=19 December 2021 |website=int.soccerway.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Tunisia vs. Mauritania - 7 October 2021 - Soccerway |url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2021/10/07/africa/wc-qualifying-africa/tunisia/mauritania/3500830/ |access-date=19 December 2021 |website=int.soccerway.com}}</ref>

Qatar hosted the [[2021 FIFA Arab Cup]]; Tunisia started with a 5–1 win against Mauritania.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Tunisia vs. Mauritania - 30 November 2021 - Soccerway |url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2021/11/30/world/arab-cup/tunisia/mauritania/3505766/ |access-date=19 December 2021 |website=int.soccerway.com}}</ref> They then suffered an unexpected defeat to [[Syria national football team|Syria]],<ref>{{Cite web |title=Syria vs. Tunisia - 3 December 2021 - Soccerway |url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2021/12/03/world/arab-cup/syria/tunisia/3505771/ |access-date=19 December 2021 |website=int.soccerway.com}}</ref> before winning against the [[United Arab Emirates national football team|United Arab Emirates]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Tunisia vs. UAE - 6 December 2021 - Soccerway |url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2021/12/06/world/arab-cup/tunisia/united-arab-emirates/3505773/ |access-date=19 December 2021 |website=int.soccerway.com}}</ref> In the quarter-finals Tunisia won against [[Oman national football team|Oman]] 2–1, and scored a 95th minute winner against Egypt in the semi-finals.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Tunisia vs. Egypt - 15 December 2021 - Soccerway |url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2021/12/15/world/arab-cup/tunisia/egypt/3505764/ |access-date=19 December 2021 |website=int.soccerway.com}}</ref> Tunisia faced [[Algeria national football team|Algeria]] in the final, losing 2–0.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Tunisia vs. Algeria - 18 December 2021 - Soccerway |url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2021/12/18/world/arab-cup/tunisia/algeria/3505770/ |access-date=19 December 2021 |website=int.soccerway.com}}</ref> The [[2021 Africa Cup of Nations]] was postponed to early 2022; in the group stage, Tunisia began with a 1–0 defeat against [[Mali national football team|Mali]], with Zambian referee [[Janny Sikazwe]] ending the match in the 85th minute.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Tunisia vs. Mali - 12 January 2022 - Soccerway |url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2022/01/12/africa/africa-cup-of-nations/tunisia/mali/3620595/ |access-date=11 June 2022 |website=int.soccerway.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Lawless |first=Josh |date=13 January 2022 |title=AFCON Official Explains Why Referee From Tunisia Vs Mali Game Blew Early For Full-Time TWICE |url=https://www.sportbible.com/football/official-explains-why-referee-from-tunisia-vs-mali-game-blew-early-20220113 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220125132253/https://www.sportbible.com/football/official-explains-why-referee-from-tunisia-vs-mali-game-blew-early-20220113 |archive-date=25 January 2022 |access-date=25 January 2022 |website=[[SPORTbible]] |publisher=The LADbible Group Ltd}}</ref> In the second match, the team achieved a 4–0 victory over Mauritania,<ref>{{Cite web |title=Tunisia vs. Mauritania - 16 January 2022 - Soccerway |url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2022/01/16/africa/africa-cup-of-nations/tunisia/mauritania/3620598/ |access-date=11 June 2022 |website=int.soccerway.com}}</ref> and lost against [[Gambia national football team|Gambia]] in the last group match. Tunisia defeated [[Nigeria national football team|Nigeria]] in the round of 16, and were eliminated by Burkina Faso.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Nigeria vs. Tunisia - 23 January 2022 - Soccerway |url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2022/01/23/africa/africa-cup-of-nations/nigeria/tunisia/3620602/ |access-date=11 June 2022 |website=int.soccerway.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Burkina Faso vs. Tunisia - 29 January 2022 - Soccerway |url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2022/01/29/africa/africa-cup-of-nations/burkina-faso/tunisia/3620625/ |access-date=11 June 2022 |website=int.soccerway.com}}</ref>

In March, Tunisia qualified for their sixth World Cup, the [[2022 FIFA World Cup|2022 tournament]] in Qatar, the first hosted by an Arab nation, after beating Mali 1–0 on aggregate, taking revenge for the earlier loss in the AFCON.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Tunisia v Mali Match Report, 29/03/2022, WC Qualification Africa |url=https://www.goal.com/en-qa/match/tunisia-v-mali/report/4s40nvofupj68q3rtdbleri1g |access-date=2022-12-08 |website=Goal.com |archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20221208081624/https://www.goal.com/en-qa/match/tunisia-v-mali/report/4s40nvofupj68q3rtdbleri1g|archive-date=2022-12-08}}</ref> They then defeated [[Chile national football team|Chile]] and [[Japan national football team|Japan]] to win the [[2022 Kirin Cup Soccer]] title for the first time,<ref>{{Cite web |title=Match Report of Chile vs Tunisia - 2022-06-10 - Kirin Cup Soccer - Global Sports Archive |url=https://globalsportsarchive.com/match/soccer/2022-06-10/chile-vs-tunisia/2690868/ |access-date=11 June 2022 |website=globalsportsarchive.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=14 June 2022 |title=Tunisia beat Japan to win Kirin Cup |url=https://www.france24.com/en/live-news/20220614-tunisia-beat-japan-to-win-kirin-cup |access-date=15 June 2022 |website=France 24 |language=en}}</ref> and [[Ferjani Sassi]] was named the best player of the tournament while his compatriot [[Issam Jebali]] finished as the top scorer with two goals.<ref>{{Cite web |date=15 June 2022 |title=Kirin Cup / Tunisie: Ferjani Sassi et Issam Jebali récompensés |url=https://africafootunited.com/kirin-cup-tunisie-ferjani-sassi-et-issam-jebali-recompenses/ |website=africafootunited|archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20220616182415/https://africafootunited.com/kirin-cup-tunisie-ferjani-sassi-et-issam-jebali-recompenses/|archive-date=2022-06-16}}</ref> Tunisia played two pre-World Cup friendlies in France in September 2022, defeating Comoros 1−0 in [[Croissy-sur-Seine]]<ref>{{Cite web|date=22 September 2022|title=Global Sports Archive|url=https://globalsportsarchive.com/match/soccer/2022-09-22/tunisia-vs-comoros/2832949/}}</ref>  and losing 5−1 to Brazil at the [[Parc des Princes]] in Paris.<ref>{{Cite web|date=27 September 2022|title=FIFA|url=https://www.fifa.com/tournaments/mens/worldcup/qatar2022/qualifiers/conmebol/match-center/400104558}}</ref> With the exception of Brazil, Tunisia's relatively good forms increased confidence on the side to break the knockout stage taboo as Tunisia found themselves grouped with world champions [[France national football team|France]], European dark horse [[Denmark national football team|Denmark]] and Asian minnows [[Australia men's national soccer team|Australia]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=2022-11-16 |title=FIFA World Cup 2022 Group D Teams: France, Australia, Denmark and Tunisia to face one another in Group D |url=https://indianexpress.com/article/sports/football/fifa-world-cup-group-d-team-guide-france-australia-denmark-tunisia-8271846/ |access-date=2022-12-08 |website=The Indian Express |language=en}}</ref> In [[2022 FIFA World Cup Group D|Group D]], Tunisia drew Euro 2020 semi-finalists Denmark 0−0 in a rather decent display by the African side.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Alexander |first=Duncan |date=2022-11-22 |title=Denmark 0-0 Tunisia: Goalless, but Far From Drab |url=https://theanalyst.com/2022/11/denmark-tunisia-stats-world-cup-2022/ |access-date=2022-12-08 |website=The Analyst |language=en}}</ref> But a 0−1 loss against Australia followed, severely hampering Tunisia's odds to progress. A 1−0 victory over France courtesy of a goal from [[Wahbi Khazri]] was not enough to seal Tunisia's place in the last 16 as Australia's [[Mathew Leckie]] goal against Denmark meant the Asian representative placed second.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2022-11-26 |title=Tunisia still in limbo after losing to Australia, must win last match |url=https://www.africanews.com/2022/11/26/australia-beats-tunisia-1-0/ |access-date=2022-12-08 |website=Africanews |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/live/2022/nov/30/tunisia-v-france-world-cup-2022-live-score-updates|title=Tunisia 1 France 0: As it happened|date=30 November 2022|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=1 December 2022}}</ref>

=== 2023–present: Difficulties and temporary decline ===
After the World Cup, the federation rejected Kadri's resignation and extended his contract until 2024.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2024-09-03 |title=Aigles de Carthage : Jalel Kadri maintenu jusqu'en 2024 |url=https://www.tuniscope.com/ar/article/347043/actualites/sport/tunisie-405007 |access-date=2024-09-03 |website=tuniscope.com |language=fr-FR}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=2022-12-30 |title=Equipe nationale : Jalel Kadri maintenu jusqu'en 2024 |url=https://lapresse.tn/2022/12/30/equipe-nationale-jalel-kadri-maintenu-jusquen-2024/ |access-date=2024-09-03 |website=La Presse de Tunisie |language=fr-FR|archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20240808200710/https://lapresse.tn/2022/12/30/equipe-nationale-jalel-kadri-maintenu-jusquen-2024/|archive-date=2024-08-08}}</ref> The team topped their [[2023 Africa Cup of Nations qualification]] group after defeating [[Libya national football team|Libya]] twice, [[Botswana national football team|Botswana]] 3–0, and a loss against [[Equatorial Guinea national football team|Equatorial Guinea]] 0–1. The team's performances began to decline, especially after the [[Tunisian Football Federation]] president, Wadie Jary, was imprisoned after accusations of financial corruption were proven.<ref>{{Cite web |title=En Tunisie, le patron de la fédération de foot écroué |url=https://www.jeuneafrique.com/1498401/politique/en-tunisie-le-patron-de-la-federation-de-foot-ecroue/ |access-date=2024-09-03 |website=JeuneAfrique.com |language=fr-FR}}</ref> On 17 November 2023, the team started [[2026 FIFA World Cup qualification (CAF)|2026 FIFA World Cup qualification]] with two victories against [[São Tomé and Príncipe national football team|São Tomé and Príncipe]] 4–0 and [[Malawi national football team|Malawi]] 1–0.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Match Report of Tunisia vs São Tomé e Príncipe - 2023-11-17 - WC Qualification |url=https://globalsportsarchive.com/match/soccer/2023-11-17/tunisia-vs-sao-tome-e-principe/3164040/ |access-date=2024-09-03 |website=globalsportsarchive.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Match Report of Malawi vs Tunisia - 2023-11-21 - WC Qualification |url=https://globalsportsarchive.com/match/soccer/2023-11-21/malawi-vs-tunisia/3164089/ |access-date=2024-09-03 |website=globalsportsarchive.com}}</ref> At the [[2023 Africa Cup of Nations]], Tunisia was drawn alongside [[Mali national football team|Mali]], [[Namibia national football team|Namibia]] and [[South Africa national soccer team|South Africa]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=CAN 2024: La Tunisie avec l'Afrique du Sud, le Mali et la Namibie |url=https://www.infosfoot.net/2023/10/12/can-2024-la-tunisie-avec-lafrique-du-sud-le-mali-et-la-namibie/ |access-date=2024-10-13 |language=fr-FR}}</ref>  

The team endured a poor performance at the tournament, as they lost to Namibia 0–1, before drawing their latter group matches against Mali 1–1 and South Africa 0–0, being eliminated from the group stage. Kadri was dismissed and [[Montasser Louhichi]] was appointed in his place temporarily. In March, the team participated in the Egyptian Capital Cup, a friendly tournament affiliated with the [[2024 FIFA Series#Egypt (ACUD Cup)|2024 FIFA Series]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=2024-03-21 |title=C'est quoi ces FIFA Séries, dernière née des compétitions internationales ? |url=https://www.sofoot.com/articles/cest-quoi-ces-fifa-series-derniere-nee-des-competitions-internationales |access-date=2024-10-13 |website=SOFOOT.com |language=fr}}</ref> The team played in the semi-final against [[Croatia national football team|Croatia]] and, after a 0–0 draw, lost on penalties 4–5.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Match Report of Tunisia vs Croatia - 2024-03-23 - ACUD Cup - Global Sports Archive |url=https://globalsportsarchive.com/match/soccer/2024-03-23/tunisia-vs-croatia/3278205/ |access-date=2024-10-13 |website=globalsportsarchive.com}}</ref> In the third-place match, the team faced [[New Zealand men's national football team|New Zealand]]; the match also ended 0–0, which ended with a 4–2 penalty shootout victory and a third-place finish for Tunisia.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Match Report of New Zealand vs Tunisia - 2024-03-26 - ACUD Cup - Global Sports Archive |url=https://globalsportsarchive.com/match/soccer/2024-03-26/new-zealand-vs-tunisia/3281966/ |access-date=2024-10-13 |website=globalsportsarchive.com}}</ref> Louhichi continued to lead the team in the third and fourth rounds of the World Cup qualifiers.<ref>{{Cite web |last=JENNY |first=Hédi |date=2024-06-03 |title=Eliminatoires mondial 2026 - À la veille de Tunisie-Guinée Équatoriale (ce mercredi à 20h00) : Un choix et une lourde responsabilité |url=https://lapresse.tn/2024/06/03/eliminatoires-mondial-2026-a-la-veille-de-tunisie-guinee-equatoriale-ce-mercredi-a-20h00-un-choix-et-une-lourde-responsabilite/ |access-date=2024-10-13 |website=La Presse de Tunisie |language=fr-FR|archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20240611053204/https://lapresse.tn/2024/06/03/eliminatoires-mondial-2026-a-la-veille-de-tunisie-guinee-equatoriale-ce-mercredi-a-20h00-un-choix-et-une-lourde-responsabilite/|archive-date=2024-06-11}}</ref> On 1 July, [[Faouzi Benzarti]] was appointed coach for the fourth time.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Boubaker |first=Saber Ben |date=2024-06-14 |title=Décisions FTF : officiel. Benzarti nouveau sélectionneur national (communiqué) |url=https://sport.tunisienumerique.com/decisions-ftf-officiel-benzarti-nouveau-selectionneur-national-communique/ |access-date=2024-10-13 |website=Sport By TN |language=fr-FR}}</ref> Under Benzarti's leadership, the team started [[2025 Africa Cup of Nations qualification]] with two wins against [[Madagascar national football team|Madagascar]] 1–0 and [[Gambia national football team|Gambia]] 2–1.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Match Report of Tunisia vs Madagascar - 2024-09-05 - TotalEnergies Africa Cup of Nations Qualification - Global Sports Archive |url=https://globalsportsarchive.com/match/soccer/2024-09-05/tunisia-vs-madagascar/3494687/ |access-date=2024-10-13 |website=globalsportsarchive.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Match Report of Gambia vs Tunisia - 2024-09-08 - TotalEnergies Africa Cup of Nations Qualification - Global Sports Archive |url=https://globalsportsarchive.com/match/soccer/2024-09-08/gambia-vs-tunisia/3494689/ |access-date=2024-10-13 |website=globalsportsarchive.com}}</ref> Tunisia then suffered a defeat at home against [[Comoros national football team|Comoros]] 0–1 and drew them away 1–1,<ref>{{Cite web |title=Match Report of Tunisia vs Comoros - 2024-10-11 - TotalEnergies Africa Cup of Nations Qualification - Global Sports Archive |url=https://globalsportsarchive.com/match/soccer/2024-10-11/tunisia-vs-comoros/3494692/ |access-date=2024-10-16 |website=globalsportsarchive.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Match Report of Comoros vs Tunisia - 2024-10-15 - TotalEnergies Africa Cup of Nations Qualification - Global Sports Archive |url=https://globalsportsarchive.com/match/soccer/2024-10-15/comoros-vs-tunisia/3494694/ |access-date=2024-10-16 |website=globalsportsarchive.com}}</ref> prompting Benzati's resignation before being replaced by [[Kais Yaâkoubi]], who led Tunisia to the AFCON.

On 10 February 2025, [[Sami Trabelsi]] returned to the team as coach twelve years after his departure, leading the team to qualifying for the [[2026 FIFA World Cup]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Sami Trabelsi, sélectionneur des Aigles de Carthage |url=https://www.mosaiquefm.net/fr/football/1378924/sami-trabelsi-selectionneur-des-aigles-de-carthage |access-date=2025-04-19 |website=Mosaique FM |language=fr}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=America |first=Mohamed Ben Romdhane scored in added time to give Tunisia a 1-0 win in Equatorial Guinea on Monday and qualification for the 2026 World Cup in North |title=Tunisia qualify for 2026 World Cup |url=https://www.beinsports.com/en-mena/football/caf-world-cup-qualifiers/articles-video/tunisia-qualify-for-2026-world-cup-2025-09-08 |access-date=2025-09-10 |website=beIN SPORTS |language=en-mena}}</ref> On 13 October 2025, Tunisia became the first team in history to qualify for the World Cup without conceding a goal, during the [[2026 FIFA World Cup qualification – CAF Group H|2026 World Cup qualifying]] campaign.<ref>{{Cite web |title=TRT Afrika - Tunisia finish 2026 World Cup qualifiers without conceding a goal |url=https://www.trtafrika.com/article/0df923946b1f |access-date=2025-10-14 |website=www.trtafrika.com |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Tunisia complete perfect World Cup qualifying campaign |url=https://www.cafonline.com/fifa-world-cup/news/tunisia-complete-perfect-world-cup-qualifying-campaign/ |access-date=2025-10-14 |publisher=Confederation of African Football |language=en-GB}}</ref> On 18 December, at [[Stade Pierre-Mauroy]] in [[Lille]], Tunisia achieved a historic 1–1 draw against [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]] in front of 40,000 spectators.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Tunisia – Brazil: A Historic Match Tunisians Must Not Miss|url=https://news-tunisia.tunisienumerique.com/tunisia-brazil-a-historic-match-tunisians-must-not-miss/|website=Tunisie|date=2025-11-13|access-date=2025-11-28|language=en-US|first=Saber|last=Boubaker}}</ref> The team entered the [[2025 FIFA Arab Cup]] in Qatar missing key players due to their European clubs refusing to release them and conflicting schedule to the also upcoming [[2025 Africa Cup of Nations]], resulting in their elimination from the group stage after a loss, a draw, and a win.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Boubaker |first=Saber |date=2025-12-07 |title=Arab Cup 2025 – Group A: Tunisia eliminated despite victory, Palestine and Syria reach quarterfinals (video) |url=https://news-tunisia.tunisienumerique.com/arab-cup-2025-group-a-tunisia-eliminated-despite-victory-palestine-and-syria-reach-quarterfinals-video/ |access-date=2025-12-08 |website=Tunisie |language=en-US}}</ref>

==Home stadium==

From 1956, the year of independence, until 1967, the 18,000-seat [[Chedly Zouiten Stadium]] was the Tunisian National Stadium.<ref name="worldstadiums.com2">{{Cite web|title=World Stadiums - Stadiums in Tunisia|url=http://www.worldstadiums.com/africa/countries/tunisia.shtml|access-date=16 June 2021|website=www.worldstadiums.com|archive-date=5 June 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110605172151/http://www.worldstadiums.com/africa/countries/tunisia.shtml|url-status=dead}}</ref> The stadium hosted matches of the [[1965 African Cup of Nations]], including the final between Tunisia and [[Ghana national football team|Ghana]], and matches from the [[1994 African Cup of Nations]]. In 1967, the [[El Menzah Stadium]], with a capacity of 39,858, was opened; it was built to host the [[1967 Mediterranean Games]]. Tunisia's first match at the stadium was played on 8 September 1967 against [[Libya national football team|Libya]]. On 11 December 1977, the stadium witnessed Tunisia qualifying for the World Cup for the first time in its history. It was completely renovated for the 1994 African Cup of Nations, and later hosted some matches for the [[2004 African Cup of Nations]]. Tunisia's last match at El Menzah was on 4 January 2017 against [[Uganda national football team|Uganda]],<ref>{{Cite web|title=Amical : Tunisie-Ouganda aura lieu à El Menzah {{!}} Revue de Sport|url=https://news.gnet.tn/archives/revue-de-sport/amical-tunisie-ouganda-aura-lieu-a-el-menzah/id-menu-323.html|website=news.gnet.tn|access-date=2025-11-28}}</ref> and the stadium has been undergoing renovations since 2022.<ref>{{cite web |access-date=26 August 2022|date=4 June 2022|language=fr|title=Démarrage imminent des travaux de rénovation du stade d’El Menzah|url=https://www.mosaiquefm.net/fr/football/1054979/demarrage-imminent-des-travaux-de-renovation-du-stade-d-el-menzah|website=mosaiquefm.net}}<!-- auto-translated from French by Module:CS1 translator -->.</ref><ref>{{cite web |access-date=26 August 2022|date=11 June 2022|language=fr|title=Réaménagement du stade olympique d'El Menzah : un budget de 100 millions de dinars|url=https://www.webmanagercenter.com/2022/06/11/487824/reamenagement-du-stade-olympique-del-menzah-un-budget-de-100-millions-de-dinars/|website=webmanagercenter.com}}<!-- auto-translated from French by Module:CS1 translator -->.</ref>

In 2001, [[Hammadi Agrebi Stadium]] (opened as 7 November Stadium) was inaugurated as Tunisia's national stadium ahead of the [[2001 Mediterranean Games]]. Located in the sports city of Radès in [[Radès]], in the southern suburb of the city [[Tunis]], has an all-seater capacity of 60,000 as the largest stadium in the country. Tunisia's first match at the stadium was on 21 August 2002 against [[France national football team|France]]. In 2004, the stadium hosted Tunisia's six matches during the 2004 African Cup of Nations, which the team won for the first time after defeating [[Morocco national football team|Morocco]] in [[2004 Africa Cup of Nations final|the final]]. The stadium is considered the team's current stronghold, as they haven't played any matches away from it since 2017.

The Tunisians often host their matches at the [[Mustapha Ben Jannet Stadium]] in [[Monastir, Tunisia|Monastir]] which has a capacity of 20,000. In addition, there are many other venues that host games, such as the [[Sousse Olympic Stadium]], which hosted a friendly match between Tunisia and [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland]] on 14 November 2012 and also hosted a match in the [[2012 Africa Cup of Nations qualification]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=[EN] La Tunisie recevra la Suisse à Sousse|url=https://tunisie-foot.com/2012/10/19/en-la-tunisie-recevra-la-suisse-a-sousse/|website=Tunisie-Foot|access-date=2025-11-28|language=fr-FR}}</ref> On 15 November 2016, The team played their first match at the [[Gabès Municipal Stadium]] against [[Mauritania national football team|Mauritania]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=[Équipe Nationale] : Tunisie – Mauritanie à Gabès|url=https://tunisie-foot.com/2016/11/01/equipe-nationale-tunisie-mauritanie-a-gabes/|website=Tunisie-Foot|access-date=2025-11-28|language=fr-FR}}</ref>
